               <msContents>
                  <summary change="#add-summary"> A copy of the <title>Bahār-i Dānish</title>
                     (Spring of Wisdom) by <persName key="person_17950016"
                        ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/17950016/">ʻInāyat Allāh (d. ca. 1671)</persName>,
                     relates the romantic adventures of Jahāndār Sulṭān and Bahravar Bānū, which
                     serves as a frame story interwoven with other tales. An unidentified scribe
                     completed this volume in <placeName>Awadh</placeName> on <date>17 Rajab 1153 AH
                        (8 Oct. 1740 CE)</date>, possibly in Awadh, where the French mercenary
                        <persName>Jean-Baptiste Joseph Gentil (d. 1799)</persName>. One of six
                     copies held in the Rylands, this redaction lacks the preface by the author's
                     younger brother and pupil <persName key="person_270970434">Muḥammad
                        Ṣāliḥ</persName> often found in other volumes, and instead opens with his
                     own introduction in which he explains how he adapted the tale from one that he
                     heard a young Brahmin recite. </summary>

                  <msItem xml:id="Persian_MS_991-item1">
                     <author key="person_17950016" ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/17950016/">
                        <persName xml:lang="fa" type="standard">ʻInāyat Allāh, d. ca.
                           1671</persName>; <lb/>
                        <persName xml:lang="ar-Latn-x-lc" type="standard">‘Ināyat Allāh Kanbū
                           Lāhūrī</persName>; <lb/>
                        <persName xml:lang="ar-Latn-x-lc" type="alt">Kanbū, ‘Ināyat
                        Allāh</persName>; <lb/>
                        <persName xml:lang="fa">عنايت الله</persName>; <lb/>
                        <persName xml:lang="fa" type="standard">عنايت الله كنبو لاهوری</persName>; <lb/>
                        <persName xml:lang="fa" type="alt">كنبو، عنايت الله</persName>
                     </author>
                     <title xml:lang="fa-Latn-x-lc" key="work_1151">Bahār-i Dānish</title>
                     <title xml:lang="fa" key="work_1151">بهار دانش</title>
                     <incipit xml:lang="fa" type="basmala"><locus from="1b" to="1b"> برگ ۱پ (folio
                           1b):</locus> و بتاج پیرایه ده دیباچه سخن حمد حگیمی است که ملک معنی را
                        بوساطت <damage>تیغ</damage> ناطقه... </incipit>
                     <!-- <explicit xml:lang="fa">
                        <locus from="209a" to="209a"> برگ ۲۰۹ر (folio 209a):</locus> سیه کاری مکن
                        چون خامهٔ خویش * بشو از چشم بر خون نامه‌ٔ خویش | زبان را گوشمالی خاموشی ده *
                        که هست از هرچه کوئی خاموشی به. </explicit>
                     <colophon xml:lang="fa">
                        <locus from="233a" to="233a"> برگ ۲۳۳ر (folio 233a):</locus> تم بالخیر کتبه
                        العبد الفقیر محمد کاتب اللاری سنة ثمان وثلاثين وتسعماية</colophon> -->

                     <textLang mainLang="fa">Persian</textLang>
                     <note>S. H. Qasemi documents 244 manuscripts and printed editions of this work.
                        C. A. Storey also notes various manuscripts and translations into English,
                        German, French, Turkish, and Urdu. For other copies of this work held in the
                        Rylands, see <ref
                           target="https://www.fihrist.org.uk/catalog/manuscript_7392"><idno>Persian
                              MS 88</idno></ref>, <ref
                           target="https://www.fihrist.org.uk/catalog/manuscript_6678">199</ref>,
                           <ref target="https://www.fihrist.org.uk/catalog/manuscript_6980"
                           >463</ref>, <ref
                           target="https://www.fihrist.org.uk/catalog/manuscript_7430">919</ref>,
                        and and <ref target="https://www.fihrist.org.uk/catalog/manuscript_26536"
                           >1017</ref>. For a glossary of terms found in this work entitled
                           <title>Rang-i Bahār</title> by ‘Abd al-Bāqī, see <ref
                           target="https://www.fihrist.org.uk/catalog/work_7106"><idno>Persian MS
                              477</idno></ref>. Note that although Rafiee-Rad implies in his catalogue of manuscripts that formerly belonged to
                        Samuel Robinson of Wilmslow, no evidence
                        suggests that this volume belonged to him, only a <persName>Mrs. </persName>.</note>
                  </msItem>
